  <his_func>&lt;p&gt;From 1627 merchant captains as Commanders ruled the area along the Berbice River in the name of the beneficiary, the Van de Pere family from Zeeland, who had been granted the settlement from the WIC. The size of the settlement was limited; in 1672 there were five sugar plantations. The Commanders were assisted by a small board of the principal planters.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;During the period of the Board of Berbice (1714-1795), Berbice was ruled by a governor, who was assisted by a Council of Policy. In all political and military affairs, the Governor had the highest authority, and in turn was subordinate to the authority of the Board. The Governor was also the president of the Council of Civil Justice.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;</his_func>
